english:
  title: Edict Commending General Kim Bu-sik, Commander of the Western Expeditionary Force
  author: Jung Hang
  language: eng
  text: |-
    To the General:

    I have reviewed your report and am fully informed of how you have captured the rebels and secured the capital.

    I reflect upon this matter thus: The rebel Zhao Kuang is a contemptible wretch of the lowest order who has long entrenched himself in difficult terrain and acted with unbridled arrogance. Though I am aware that we could marshal our forces and soldiers to obliterate him utterly, leaving not a trace of his line, I have hesitated for these reasons: the Western Capital is where our founding ancestor first established the royal enterprise, and the multitudes dwelling there are all my beloved children. How could I bring myself to slaughter them entirely? For this reason, I issued proclamations of admonition, repeated again and again, hoping that Zhao Kuang and his followers would change their hearts and surrender, thereby experiencing the compassion of the court. Of this you are well aware.

    But after the arch-villain Myo-cheong was eliminated by your forces, a miscalculation at Jeol-lyeong changed the enemy's circumstances, and victory could no longer be achieved in mere days. You, possessed of both civil and martial talents, bearing the responsibilities of general and minister, have won the hearts of your soldiers through magnanimity and demonstrated keen judgment in all matters. Your stratagems for confronting and controlling the enemy require no consultation—they already dwell perfected in your breast.

    First, you constructed fortifications and palisades to allow your troops rest. Then you raised earthen ramparts to crush the enemy's encampment. When the great army surged forward, the rebel lair stood empty. The enemy's ranks crumbled at mere rumor of your approach; they surrendered with bound hands. Shortly thereafter, without striking a single blow, you brought the entire city to submission as easily as turning your palm. Through timely decisiveness, you have achieved glory that will endure ten thousand ages. Without your brilliant, resolute, and flawless strategy, I could never have accomplished what I entrusted to you.

    My admiration knows no bounds. I hereby dispatch the imperial envoys—Attendant Official Yi Ji-jeo and Deputy Envoy Lin Yi—bearing this edict to convey my recognition and bestow the prescribed rewards as detailed in the accompanying list. Receive these with due respect. Let all officers and soldiers of the Five Armies document their outstanding deeds, each case to be memorialized for consideration of appropriate honors and rewards. This edict is issued that all may know.

    As spring warmth prevails, I trust you are in good health. These words cannot express all my sentiments.
  footnotes:
    - Zhao Kuang represents the rebel leader Choe Hong (or a similar historical figure), whose name has been sinicized in the original document.
    - Myo-cheong (妙淸) was a real historical Buddhist monk and rebel who led an insurrection; his death is mentioned as a turning point in the campaign.
    - Jeol-lyeong (岊嶺) refers to a strategic mountain pass where a military setback occurred, complicating the subsequent campaign.
    - The 'Five Armies' (五軍) refers to the military divisions of the Goryeo kingdom's armed forces.
